      <!-- Step-by-step hanging guide -->
      <div class="card">
        <h2>Step-by-Step Wallpaper Hanging Guide</h2>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>1. Prepare the walls</strong><p>Remove old wallpaper, fill holes and cracks with spackle, sand smooth, and apply a wallpaper primer/sizing. Clean walls ensure strong adhesion and easy removal later.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>2. Measure and cut strips</strong><p>Measure wall height and add 4 inches (2 inches top and bottom for trimming). For patterned wallpaper, add one full pattern repeat to each strip length to ensure alignment.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>3. Establish a plumb line</strong><p>Use a level or plumb bob to draw a perfectly vertical line near a corner. This ensures your first strip hangs straight — walls and corners are rarely perfectly plumb.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>4. Apply paste and book the paper</strong><p>For unpasted wallpaper, apply paste evenly with a roller. Fold the pasted sides together ("booking") and let it rest 3–5 minutes so the paste activates and the paper expands evenly.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>5. Hang the first strip</strong><p>Align the strip to your plumb line, leaving 2 inches of overlap at the ceiling. Smooth from the center outward with a wallpaper brush or smoother to remove air bubbles.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>6. Match patterns and continue</strong><p>Butt each new strip against the previous one — do not overlap seams. Slide the strip up or down to match the pattern before smoothing. Wipe excess paste from the surface immediately.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>7. Trim and finish</strong><p>Use a sharp utility knife and a broad knife as a guide to trim excess paper at the ceiling, baseboard, and around outlets. Change blades frequently — dull blades tear wet wallpaper.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>8. Handle corners carefully</strong><p>Never wrap a full strip around a corner. Cut the strip to wrap 1/2 inch past the corner, then hang the remaining piece overlapping that 1/2 inch and aligned to a new plumb line.</p></div>
      </div>

      <!-- SEO / FAQ Content -->
      <div class="seo-content">
        <h2>How to Calculate How Much Wallpaper You Need</h2>
        <p>Calculating wallpaper requirements involves measuring your total wall area, subtracting openings, and dividing by the usable coverage per roll. The key formula:</p>
        <div class="formula-box">Rolls Needed = Usable Wall Area ÷ Usable Coverage per Roll × (1 + Waste Factor)</div>
        <p>For example, a 12 × 10 foot room with 8-foot ceilings has a wall perimeter of 44 feet and a gross wall area of 352 sq ft. Subtract two windows (30 sq ft) and one door (21 sq ft) to get 301 sq ft of usable wall area. A standard US roll (20.5" × 33 ft) covers about 56 sq ft, but after pattern matching and trimming, you get roughly 28 sq ft of usable coverage. That means you need about <strong>12 single rolls</strong>.</p>

        <h2>Understanding Wallpaper Roll Sizes</h2>
        <p>Wallpaper comes in different roll sizes depending on the manufacturer and region:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>US Standard:</strong> 20.5 inches wide × 33 feet long (~56 sq ft per single roll)</li>
          <li><strong>European Standard:</strong> 21 inches wide × 33 feet long (~58 sq ft per single roll)</li>
          <li><strong>Wide/Commercial:</strong> 27 inches wide × 27 feet long (~54 sq ft per single roll)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Wallpaper is priced per single roll but usually sold in double rolls (bolts). A double roll is twice the length, giving you more flexibility in cutting strips and less waste overall.</p>

        <h2>How Pattern Repeat Affects Waste</h2>
        <p>Pattern repeat is the distance between identical points in a repeating design. There are three types:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>No repeat (solid/texture):</strong> Minimal waste — each strip can be cut to exact wall height plus trimming allowance.</li>
          <li><strong>Straight match:</strong> The pattern aligns at the same point on each strip. Waste depends on repeat height — larger repeats mean more waste per strip.</li>
          <li><strong>Drop match (half-drop):</strong> The pattern aligns offset by half the repeat distance. Every other strip must be shifted, increasing waste slightly more than a straight match.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>A 24-inch pattern repeat on 8-foot walls wastes approximately 12 inches per strip. On a standard roll that yields 4 strips, this adds up to 4 sq ft of waste per roll — which can mean needing 1–3 extra rolls for a typical room.</p>

        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <h3>How much wallpaper do I need?</h3>
        <p>Measure the perimeter of your room (all wall lengths added together) and multiply by the ceiling height to get the gross wall area. Subtract windows and doors, then divide by the usable coverage per roll. Add 10% for waste — more if using patterned wallpaper with a large repeat.</p>

        <h3>What is a standard wallpaper roll size?</h3>
        <p>A US standard single roll is 20.5 inches wide by 33 feet long, covering about 56 square feet. European rolls are 21 inches wide by 33 feet. Wallpaper is typically sold in double rolls (66 feet long) but priced per single roll.</p>

        <h3>What is pattern repeat and why does it matter?</h3>
        <p>Pattern repeat is the vertical distance between one point in a design and the next identical point. A 21-inch repeat means the pattern repeats every 21 inches. Larger repeats waste more wallpaper because each strip must be aligned, causing unused material between cuts.</p>

        <h3>How do I account for windows and doors?</h3>
        <p>Measure the width and height of each opening, multiply to get the area, then subtract the total from your gross wall area. A standard door is about 21 sq ft (3 × 7 ft) and a standard window is about 15 sq ft (3 × 5 ft). This calculator lets you add each opening individually for accuracy.</p>

        <h3>Should I buy extra wallpaper rolls?</h3>
        <p>Always. Buy at least 10% more than calculated. Dye lots vary between production runs, so matching wallpaper later can be nearly impossible. Most retailers accept returns of unopened rolls, so there's little risk in over-ordering.</p>

        <h3>How much does it cost to wallpaper a room?</h3>
        <p>Material costs range from $20–$100+ per roll. A typical 12×10 room needs 10–14 rolls, so materials run $200–$1,400 depending on wallpaper quality. Add $25–$50 for paste and supplies. Professional installation adds $25–$75 per roll for labor.</p>

        <h3>What is the difference between a single roll and a double roll?</h3>
        <p>A single roll is the pricing unit — a double roll is the physical product. A double roll is twice as long (66 ft vs 33 ft) and yields more strips per bolt, reducing waste. Always confirm whether the listed price is per single or double roll.</p>

